⏺ Two separate things, both very doable:

  ---
  User prompts (AI generation)

  User types "build a 3:1 gear reduction" → Claude
   generates the assembly JSON → site validates +
  visualizes it.

  What it takes:
  - Convert the static site to a Vercel project
  with one serverless function (/api/generate)
  - That function calls Claude Sonnet with the
  parts library + format instructions in context
  - Add a text input + "Generate" button to the UI
  - Store ANTHROPIC_API_KEY as a Vercel env var
  - Add rate limiting (Upstash Redis, same setup
  as cadarena) to prevent abuse
  - Cost: ~$0.003 per generation

  ~1 day of work

  ---
  Expanded parts library

  Current: 23 parts. Real Technic catalog is ~200
  useful parts (all beam sizes, angle beams, cross
   blocks, turntables, pneumatics, etc.) and the
  full LDraw library is 17k.

  What it takes:
  - For ~200 parts: manually curate from LDraw
  database, add metadata (teeth, radius, holes,
  connection points) → a few days of data work
  - For full 17k: need a semantic search tool so
  the model can query "find a gear with 20 teeth"
  rather than having everything in context at once
   → more infrastructure

  ~2-3 days for a solid 200-part library

  ---
  Together they make the thing actually
  interesting — user describes a mechanism, model
  finds the right parts, generates the assembly,
  you see it in 3D and verify all connections.
  That's the actual benchmark loop.

